<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-26T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-26T05:00:00-05:00" n="637" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d637">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5431/256: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-26T11:00:00+01:00">October 26, 1935—11
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 26—6:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>43. Department’s 66, October 23, 2 p.m. Culbertson and Hawks saw
                                Stucki last evening. He stated that Swiss watch manufacturers
                                recently told him that if the present American proposals on watches
                                are not bettered they would prefer that no agreement be signed since
                                tariff on adjusted movements makes their position worse instead of
                                better. Stucki telegraphed Nef on the 23rd to investigate and
                                report. I am seeing Stucki Monday and would appreciate Department’s
                                comment on the above prior to that time.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>